etm_info:
Most likely substantivized[1] from Proto-Balto-Slavic *b√°lÀÄtas (‚Äúfaint, white‚Äù). Cognate with Lithuanian b√°ltas (‚Äúwhite‚Äù), bal√† (‚Äúswamp‚Äù), Latvian balts (‚Äúwhite‚Äù), and the second part of Old Prussian placename Namuyn-balt.
The semantic connection between "white" and "swamp, mud" is not obvious, but has been attested in many languages. Beside the mentioned Lithuanian, also in e.g., Old Polish biel (‚Äúmud, swamp‚Äù) (< *bƒõl—å, from *bƒõl—ä (‚Äúwhite‚Äù)). This is probably due to the widespread presence of the marsh grass called cottongrass (genus Eriophorum), whose the white fluffy seed heads are white, or the color of the dried clay taking light hue, depending on soil.
Though formally and semantically derivable from Proto-Indo-European *b ∞elH- (‚Äúwhite‚Äù), with cognates such as Albanian balt√´ (‚Äúmud‚Äù), Romanian baltƒÉ (‚Äúmud, swamp‚Äù) and Greek Œ≤Œ¨ŒªœÑŒøœÇ (v√°ltos, ‚Äúswamp‚Äù), it is often considered an Illyrian substratum word (or from another, unidentified substrate language; cf. Proto-Slavic *bala (‚Äúmarsh‚Äù)) due to the fact that most of the cognates are restricted to the Balkan peninsula, or its surroundings. However, these can also be borrowings from early Slavic; indirect evidence shows that the Slavic liquid metathesis and pleophony happened well after the spread of Slavic to the Balkans and the word must have been pronounced as *balta or *bolto as recently as the late 8th century.

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *nisd√°, from Proto-Indo-European *nisd√≥s.
Baltic cognates include Lithuanian l√¨zdas, Latvian ligzds, ligzda. The Slavic forms show a different anlaut from the Baltic forms; the Slavic forms have gained an initial *gn- on the basis of some other model such as *gnoj—å (‚Äúmanure, pus‚Äù), though which particular word was used as a model is hard to say. The choice of *gnoj—å (‚Äúmanure, pus‚Äù) also has a possible advantage in that it can account for the presence of *ƒõ in *gnƒõzdo, otherwise an anomaly. Skok instead explains the anomalous cluster and the many reflexes in Serbo-Croatian as resulting from various dissimilations of the dental consonants. Mel‚Äônyƒçuk suggests the initial part of the word was reconstructed on the model of *gnƒõti or its precursor.

Per LIV, from Proto-Balto-Slavic *krƒÅÃÅÀÄtei + *-sti (d ∞√©-conjugation), perhaps back-formed from the proto d ∞i-imperative, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kreh‚ÇÇ- (‚Äúto take, to gather‚Äù). Cognate with ye-present Latvian kr√¢t (‚Äúto gather, to heap‚Äù).

From *svob—å, from *svoj—å + *-oda. For the suffix cf. *agoda.
From the root *svo- (‚Äúself-‚Äù) (masculine), *sva- (‚Äúself-‚Äù) (feminine) (cognate with Sanskrit ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ¬†f (sva)), from Proto-Indo-European *swo-b ∞o-/*swe-b ∞o- and Proto-Slavic *buditi, from Proto-Indo-European *b ∞owd ∞√©yeti, causative of *b ∞ewd ∞- (‚Äúto be awake, aware‚Äù) (cognate with Sanskrit ‡§¨‡•ã‡§ß‡§Ø‡§§‡§ø (bodh√°yati)) - meaning literally "condition of being aware of oneself" or more precisely "the gift (ability) of being aware of oneself", whereby condition/ability, or precisely the gift, Proto-Slavic *dar—ä and Polish dar, from Proto-Indo-European *d√©h‚ÇÉrom, related to Sanskrit ‡§ß‡§æ‡§§‡•É (dhƒÅt·πõÃÅ) "donor, giver, supporter, creator‚Ä¶" and Sanskrit ‡§¶‡§æ‡§§‡•É (dƒÅt·πõ, ‚Äúgiver‚Äù), agent noun of ‡§¶‡§¶‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (dadƒÅti, ‚Äúto give‚Äù) is being just indicated by d or d ∞ - compare the English expression "to be so free" and the extensive use of shortforms and apostrophes in English language. The word thus means "the given ability to be aware of (and express) oneself". Same extension in Latvian atsvabinƒÅt (‚Äúto free‚Äù), Old Prussian subs, Proto-Germanic *swƒìbaz¬†m, *sibj≈ç¬†f, Latin Sabƒ´nƒ´, Sabellƒ´, Samnium.

etm_info:
By surface *kopr—ä (‚Äúdill‚Äù) +‚Äé *-iv—ä +‚Äé *-a, probably from the original sense steaming, scalding found in the root *kopnƒõti (‚Äúto melt (for snow), to hope‚Äù), *kypƒõti (‚Äúto boil up‚Äù), because of the burning feel on the human skin on touch of this plant. For similar semantic development, compare dial. Czech ≈æe≈ôica (‚Äúnettle‚Äù) (from Proto-Slavic *≈æar—ä (‚Äúembers‚Äù)), German Brennessel (‚Äúnettle‚Äù) (from German brennen (‚Äúto burn‚Äù)), Dutch brandnetel from branden (‚Äúto burn‚Äù), Latin ≈´rtƒ´ca from ≈´rere (‚Äúto burn‚Äù). Unlikely from the sense aroma applied in *kopr—ä and attested in the related lemmas Lithuanian kv√£pas (‚Äúaroma‚Äù), Lithuanian kvƒópti (‚Äúto smell, to breath‚Äù), since nettle does not have any particular smell.
A secondary reason of the relation to *kopr—ä (‚Äúdill‚Äù) may be the use of both as a food supplement.
The form *kropiva¬†to which some forms point is modelled after *kropiti (‚Äúto besprinkle‚Äù) conceiving the crop‚Äôs conspicuous manner of distribution.

ESSJa treats it as as a single headword, Derksen as two (separating meanings "harrow" and "guarded entrance, barrier"), and S≈Çawski as three ("harrow", "defended/defending object" and "membrane").
The meaning "harrow" is from Proto-Indo-European *b ∞orh‚ÇÉneh‚ÇÇ, o-grade derivation from *b ∞erh‚ÇÉ- (‚Äúto hit with a sharp instrument‚Äù). etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *meiÀÄr√°s, from Proto-Indo-European *mey(H)-r√≥-s, its Baltic cognates are: Lithuanian mieras (‚Äúpeace‚Äù), Latvian mi√™rs (‚Äúpeace‚Äù), compare also Albanian mir√´ (‚Äúgood‚Äù).
There may be two Indo-European roots involved, *mey- (‚Äúto tie, strengthen‚Äù) and *mehh‚ÇÅ- (‚Äúsoft, mild‚Äù).
Root-cognates (with different suffixes) include, with the former: Ancient Greek ŒºŒØœÑŒøœÇ (m√≠tos, ‚Äúwarp thread‚Äù), Proto-Indo-Iranian *mitr√°s (literally ‚Äú(that which) causes binding‚Äù) (Old Persian êé∑êé∞êéº (mi-Œ∏-r), and Sanskrit ‡§Æ‡§ø‡§§‡•ç‡§∞ (mitra)); with the latter:  Proto-Slavic *mil—ä (‚Äúnice, gentle, mild‚Äù), Latin mƒ´tis (‚Äúmild, calm, peaceful‚Äù).[1]
The dual meaning of "peace" and "world" is unique to Slavic, and scholarly opinion is divided on whether this is a purely semantic development (via a meaning of "pact, friendship" to "community, society" to "ecumene, inhabited world") or alternatively an early conflation of two words, with the meaning "world" derived only from the root meaning "to bind", and the meaning "peace" derived from the root meaning "gentle, mild".[2]

Past passive participle of unattested verb (nouns: *ƒçar—ä, *ƒçara (‚Äúmagic, sorcery‚Äù)) that is the exact equivalent of the Lithuanian kerƒóÃÅti (‚Äúto bewitch‚Äù). Past passive participle of *ƒçerti (‚Äúto cut‚Äù). This etymology is supported by the fact that in many beliefs, evil spiritis were often mutilated, cf. Polish kusy (‚Äúdevil‚Äù), Bulgarian –∫—äÃÅ—Å (k«éÃÅs, ‚Äúdevil‚Äù) from Proto-Slavic *k«´s—ä (‚Äúbitten off; short; tailless‚Äù). From Proto-Balto-Slavic *tel- + *-ƒô (diminutive suffix), cognate with Latvian teƒº≈°, telƒìns, Lithuanian t·∫Ωlias. Three types of hypotheses exist for the origin of the root:

Machek tentatively proposes as an alternative ad hoc simiplificaiton of (formally incompatible) Proto-Indo-European *wet√©las (‚Äúyearling‚Äù) cognate with Latin vitulus (‚Äúcalf‚Äù), Ancient Greek ·ºîœÑŒ±ŒªŒøŒΩ (√©talon, ‚Äúyearling‚Äù) and akin to Proto-Germanic *we√æruz (‚Äúwether, year-old lamb‚Äù).
Temematic origin: Per Holzer, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *d ∞eh‚ÇÅ(y)- (‚Äúto suckle‚Äù) via a hypothetical Indo-European dialect which devoiced aspirated stops. If right, then akin to directly inherited Proto-Slavic *dƒõtƒô (‚Äúchild‚Äù) and further Latin filius (‚Äúson‚Äù), Albanian dele (‚Äúewe‚Äù). Disputed by Matasoviƒá.

etm_info:
The exact etymology is unclear. The dominant standpoints are:

Per Derksen, possibly cognate with Latin terg≈ç (‚Äúto wipe‚Äù), with semantic distortion by influence of *d—årgati (‚Äúto tear‚Äù).
Per Vasmer, connected with Sanskrit ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•É‡§π‡§§‡§ø (st·πõh√°ti, ‚Äúto crush‚Äù), ‡§§‡•É‡§£‡•á‡§¢‡§ø (t·πõ·πá√©·∏çhi, ‚Äúshattered, broken‚Äù), perfect ‡§§‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§π (tatarha), perf. pass. part. ‡§§‡•É‡§¢ (t·πõ·∏çh√°). Doubtfully connected with Latin trah≈ç (‚Äúto drag‚Äù), Gothic êå∏êå∞êåπêçÇêå∫êçâ (√æairk≈ç, ‚Äúhole‚Äù).
Per Chernykh, from Proto-Indo-European *terg ∞-, extended version of *ter- (‚Äúto rub‚Äù), cognate with Proto-Slavic *terti, Latin ter≈ç.
Over time, the term has undergone a semantic drift in certain thematic environments, giving rise to figurative terms such as Russian —Ç—Ä–æ–≥–∞—Ç—å (trogat π, ‚Äúto affect, to arouse emotionally‚Äù) and Bulgarian —Ç—Ä—ä–≥–≤–∞–º (tr«égvam), Macedonian —Ç—Ä–≥–Ω–µ (trgne, ‚Äúto depart‚Äù). The later semantic development is analogous with Italian partire (‚Äúto go away‚Äù), French partir (‚Äúto depart‚Äù) which descend from Latin partƒ´re (‚Äúto separate‚Äù).

Unknown. No reliable non-Slavic cognates have been identified to date (including in Baltic languages, which is surprising considering some archaic features of the word).
Semantically close Ancient Greek œÄŒ∑ŒªœåœÇ (pƒìl√≥s, ‚Äúclay, mud, bog‚Äù) (also Doric œÄ·æ±ŒªœåœÇ (pƒÅl√≥s), which could indicate possible derivation from *k ∑ƒÅlos) is unexplained as well, since derivation from a common IE **k ∑eh‚ÇÇlos is prevented by accentuation (Hirt's law). Beekes suspected it to be a Pre-Greek (non-IE substrate) borrowing.
Something similar is Latin squƒÅlus (‚Äúdirty, unkempt‚Äù): there's no etymology, sematics seems to be close and according to de Vaan, sequence "squ-" indicates it isn't an inherited word. However, the root may be derived to squƒÅlor (‚Äúfilth, roughness of the surface‚Äù) and squƒÅma (‚Äúscale‚Äù) even though those lack an etymology as well.
Sanskrit ‡§ï‡§æ‡§≤ (kƒÅla, ‚Äúblack, very dark blue‚Äù) is either a Dravidian borrowing or a late development, thus unrelated.

Disputed. Derksen lists three hypotheses:

From an elongated ≈ç-grade Proto-Indo-European *g ∞≈çd-, from root *g ∞ed- (‚Äúto take, to hold, to find‚Äù). Cognate with Proto-Germanic *getanƒÖ (‚Äúto get, to perceive, to acquire‚Äù) (the source of English get) and akin to ne-infix presents Ancient Greek œáŒ±ŒΩŒ¥Œ¨ŒΩœâ (khand√°n≈ç, ‚Äúto contain‚Äù), Latin prehend≈ç (‚Äúto seize, to take‚Äù). Favoured by Vasmer.
Related to synonymous *gatati, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *g ∑et-, *g ∑ed- (‚Äúto say, to speak‚Äù). If so, then akin to Proto-Germanic *kwe√æanƒÖ (‚Äúto say‚Äù), Sanskrit ‡§ó‡§¶‡§§‡§ø (g√°dati) (perhaps originating from a mixture of *gat- with ‡§µ‡§¶‡§§‡§ø (v√°dati)). Supported by Berneker, Chernykh, Seebold, who also give as cognates Lithuanian god√≥ti (‚Äúto honor, to respect, to think, to believe‚Äù), Latvian g√£d√¢t (‚Äúto take care, to look after‚Äù) (further related to Lithuanian god·∫Ωlƒó (‚Äúthought, guess‚Äù), g√πosti (‚Äúto care‚Äù)).
Possibly related to Proto-Slavic *goditi (‚Äúto please‚Äù), *gaƒèati (‚Äúto aim, to make relation‚Äù), Lithuanian gu√µdas (‚Äúworth, honour‚Äù), Latvian gad√Æt (‚Äúto happen to find‚Äù), from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞ed ∞- (‚Äúto suit, to join, to gather‚Äù). Favoured by S≈Çawski, Zubat√Ω.

etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *au≈°(t)ra- (‚Äúdawn, morning‚Äù), from Proto-Indo-European *h‚ÇÇews-ro- (‚Äúof the dawn or morning, matutinal; eastern‚Äù), from *h‚ÇÇews- (‚Äúdawn; east‚Äù). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian au≈°r√†, dial. au≈°tr√† (‚Äúdawn‚Äù), Latvian √†ustra, a≈©stra (‚Äúdawn‚Äù). Indo-European cognates include Ancient Greek Œ±·ΩîœÅ·æ± (a√∫rƒÅ, ‚Äú(esp. cool) breeze, fresh air of the morning‚Äù), Latin auster (‚Äúsouth wind‚Äù), Proto-Germanic *austrƒÖ (‚Äúeast‚Äù), Proto-Germanic *Austr«≠ (‚ÄúEaster, springtime; name of a goddess‚Äù) (presumably from the goddess of the dawn, lust, fertility and spring, associated with the beginning of the year).
A variant *jutro appears in West Slavic, Slovenian and Serbo-Croatian, and is also attested in Old Church Slavonic, but considered secondary; there are further Slavic lexemes that display an alternation *ju- in West and South Slavic vs. *u- in East Slavic. Variants with *(j)ustr- point to *ustr- < *usr-,[1] the loss of -s- being either due to dissimilation[2] or perhaps due to the law of open syllables, if the -s- was variably assigned to the end of the first syllable. According to Kortlandt, the acute on the root implies a zero-grade variant (which would have parallels in Sanskrit ‡§â‡§∏‡•ç‡§∞ (usr√°-, ‚Äúreddish, ruddy, bright, matutinal‚Äù), ‡§â‡§∏‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ (usrƒÅÃÅ-, ‚Äúdawn, morning‚Äù)), which, however, is not attested.[3] The intrusive -t- is regular in Proto-Slavic, compare *ostr—ä, *strumy.

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞rob-√©ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞reb-; meanings "to rake" in daughter languages from confusion with the root *g ∞reb ∞- (see Proto-Slavic *gret√¨ (‚Äúto dig, to rake, to scrape‚Äù)). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian gr√≥bti (‚Äúto seize‚Äù), Latvian gr√¢bt (‚Äúto seize‚Äù). Indo-European cognates include Old Norse gr√°pa (‚Äúto seize‚Äù). The same confusion appears to have happened elsewhere; compare Sanskrit ‡§ó‡•É‡§π‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (g·πõh·πáƒÅÃÅti), ‡§ó‡•É‡§≠‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (g·πõbh·πáƒÅÃÅti, ‚Äúto seize, to hold, to take‚Äù). Avestan: grab- ‚Äòto grab, seize, take‚Äô, Old Persian: grab- ‚Äòto seize (as possesion), Persian ⁄Øÿ±ŸÅÿ™ŸÜ‚Äé (gereftan), Ÿæÿ∞€åÿ±ŸÅÿ™ŸÜ‚Äé (paziroftan).[1] English grab vs. Gothic êå≤êçÇêå∞êå±êå∞êåΩ (graban, ‚Äúto dig‚Äù), all of which come from *g ∞reb ∞-. Derksen does not derive this verb from *g ∞reb ∞- due to Winter's law, which is required to produce the acute *-a- of the Slavic root but would not operate in *g ∞reb ∞-.
Per Vasmer, Chernykh and Trubachev, this verb in fact derives from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞rob-√©ye-ti, from *g ∞reb-; see also Proto-Slavic *gret√¨. Chernykh describes it as the causative of *gret√¨.

etm_info:
Of uncertain origin.
The central Indo-European word for "fish" *d ∞«µ ∞u- (‚Äúfish‚Äù) (yielding Ancient Greek ·º∞œáŒ∏œçœÇ (ikhth√∫s), Lithuanian ≈æuv√¨s, Old Armenian ’±’∏÷Ç’Ø’∂ (jukn)) would have given Proto-Slavic v-stem **zy (genitive **z—äve, accusative **z—äv—å), and was, as the theory goes, avoided by fishermen due to taboo, or because it would have sounded too similar to the verb *z—ävati (‚Äúto call‚Äù).
Some of the proposed etymologies include:

Toporov: From Early Proto-Slavic *r≈≥ÃÑbƒÅ, which is then comparable to *rƒôb—ä (‚Äúspeckled, motley, variegated‚Äù), with fish scales being the semantic connection. For a similar development compare *p—åstry (‚Äúsalmonid fish‚Äù), originally "the colorful/variegated one" < *p—åstr—ä (‚Äúvariegated‚Äù).
Loewenthal: From earlier *r≈≥ÃÑbƒÅ, but instead from Proto-Indo-European *wremb- (‚Äúto twist around‚Äù), akin to Proto-Germanic *wrimpanƒÖ (‚Äúto wince‚Äù), Ancient Greek ·ø•Œ≠ŒºŒ≤œâ (rh√©mb≈ç, ‚Äúto roam, to turn in circles‚Äù). Doubted by Vasmer.
Vaillant: Perhaps originally a collection/action noun from *ryti (‚Äúto dig, to snout‚Äù) +‚Äé *-ba, initially referring to the process ‚Äúfishing‚Äù and later (by abstraction) to the yield ‚Äúfish‚Äù.
Mladenov: Akin to Proto-Slavic *rux—ä (‚Äúmovement, deformation‚Äù), *ryxl—ä (‚Äúswift, quick‚Äù), from Proto-Indo-European *h‚ÇÉrew- (‚Äúto hurry‚Äù).
Jakobson, Schmalstieg, Snoj: From Proto-Balto-Slavic *j≈´ÀÄr- (‚Äúwater, swamp, pond‚Äù), whence Lithuanian j≈´ÃÅra (‚Äúsea‚Äù), Latvian j≈´ra (‚Äúsea‚Äù) and perhaps akin to Proto-Slavic *juriti (‚Äúto charge, to plunge‚Äù), *jur—äk—ä (‚Äúwhisk, agile‚Äù), with a rare metathesis *≈´r- > *r≈´- + the suffix *-ba for forming abstract nouns.
Early scholars (Uhlenbeck, Berneker, Mikkola, Walde-Hofmann) had tentatively compared the Slavic word with Old High German r≈´ppa (‚Äúcaterpillar‚Äù) or Latin rubƒìta (‚Äúbramble toad‚Äù), which nowadays are commonly viewed as unrelated.

Br√ºckner, Mladenov, S≈Çawski: In association with the vibrant, auburn coloration of (some) marshes. Parallel to likely cognate Proto-Slavic *bagr—ä (‚Äúhue‚Äù), whence Ukrainian –±–∞–≥—Ä–∏ÃÅ–Ω–∞ (bahr√Ωna, ‚Äúswamp‚Äù), Slovak bahurina (‚Äúwetland‚Äù).

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *ker-, *kƒìr-, from Proto-Indo-European *k ∑er- (‚Äúto do, make, build‚Äù). Cognate with Sanskrit ‡§ï‡§∞‡•ã‡§§‡§ø (kar√≥ti), Lithuanian k√πrti.
Slavic forms with *ƒçar- presuppose a nominal lengthened-grade derivation, i.e. Proto-Balto-Slavic *kƒìr- (Lithuanian k·∫Ωras (‚Äúcharm, magic‚Äù)). Serbo-Croatian feminine i-stem is probably an archaism - lengthened grade is expected in PIE root nouns which yield Balto-Slavic i-stems. The PIE root probably already had magical connotations, i.e. denoting remote action by magical means. (Can this(+) etymology be sourced?).

etm_info:
Of uncertain kinship. Relatable to Lithuanian bal√°nda and Latvian balodene (‚Äúgoosefoot¬†(Chenopodium); orach (Atriplex gen. et spp.)‚Äù), and even a distant relationship to Proto-Germanic *meld«≠ (‚Äúgoosefoot; orach‚Äù) cannot be excluded. A derivation from Proto-Indo-European *alb ∞√≥s (‚Äúwhite‚Äù) begs the semantical question whether there are characteristic white parts with the orach or chenopod, any more relevantly than to artificially find the name Chenopodium album. Ancient Greek ŒªŒ¨œÄŒ±Œ∏ŒøŒΩ (l√°pathon, ‚Äúsorrel‚Äù, a meaning also present in Turkish) may be related by being borrowed from an Indo-European language close to Balto-Slavic as Dacian, Thracian, or Illyrian, connected to Albanian l√´pjet√´ (‚Äúsorrel‚Äù), wheras Ancient Greek Œ≤Œª·øêÃÅœÑŒøŒΩ (bl√≠ton, ‚Äúpurple amaranth‚Äù)¬†might be an inherited cognate.
Cihac suggests that the word is interrelated with Hungarian l√°b (‚Äúfoot, leg‚Äù) and thus derives from Uralic, comparing Romanian laba g√¢»ôtei (‚Äúchenopod‚Äù, literally ‚Äúgoose paw‚Äù), syn. talpa g√¢»ôtei (‚Äúgoose sole‚Äù), and the botanical Chenopodium from œáŒÆŒΩ (kh·∏ón, ‚Äúgoose‚Äù) +‚Äé œÄŒøœçœÇ (po√∫s, ‚Äúfoot‚Äù) (but most of such like German G√§nsefu√ü (‚Äúchenopod‚Äù) and English goosefoot are calqued from the taxonomic; instead compare Middle Armenian ’¢’°’¶’∏÷Ç’Ø (bazuk, ‚Äúbeet‚Äù, literally ‚Äúarm‚Äù)). Nonetheless Georg Holzer ascribes the word to the Indo-European substrate he calls ‚ÄúTemematic‚Äù, deriving in it as a bah√∫vrƒ´hi¬†compound of Proto-Indo-European *h‚ÇÅel- (‚Äúgoose‚Äù, according to him) and *p·πìds (‚Äúfoot‚Äù).
Of the same origin is a Common Turkic term *(a)labVda everywhere meaning plants of the Atripliceae syn. Chenopodieae tribe that is not found in Chuvash¬†or Yakut.
Descendance from Proto-Iranian *(h)rabƒÅÃÅ≈° ~ *(h)rabac√°h (‚Äúrhubarb‚Äù) (see there for more) may explain this geographical picture, rhubarb (Rheum) and sorrel (Rumex) anciently being confusables of the same botanical tribe, compare the concept of monk's rhubarb (Rumex alpinus and Rumex patientia, which is also a meaning of Ancient Greek ŒªŒ¨œÄŒ±Œ∏ŒøŒΩ (l√°pathon), with superficial similarity to the orach (Atriplex) and goosefoot (Chenopodium) vegetable plants.

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞rob-√©ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞reb-; meanings "to rake" in daughter languages from confusion with the root *g ∞reb ∞- (see Proto-Slavic *gret√¨ (‚Äúto dig, to rake, to scrape‚Äù)). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian gr√≥bti (‚Äúto seize‚Äù), Latvian gr√¢bt (‚Äúto seize‚Äù). Indo-European cognates include Old Norse gr√°pa (‚Äúto seize‚Äù). The same confusion appears to have happened elsewhere; compare Sanskrit ‡§ó‡•É‡§π‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (g·πõh·πáƒÅÃÅti), ‡§ó‡•É‡§≠‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (g·πõbh·πáƒÅÃÅti, ‚Äúto seize, to hold, to take‚Äù). Avestan: grab- ‚Äòto grab, seize, take‚Äô, Old Persian: grab- ‚Äòto seize (as possesion), Persian ⁄Øÿ±ŸÅÿ™ŸÜ‚Äé (gereftan), Ÿæÿ∞€åÿ±ŸÅÿ™ŸÜ‚Äé (paziroftan).[1] English grab vs. Gothic êå≤êçÇêå∞êå±êå∞êåΩ (graban, ‚Äúto dig‚Äù), all of which come from *g ∞reb ∞-. Derksen does not derive this verb from *g ∞reb ∞- due to Winter's law, which is required to produce the acute *-a- of the Slavic root but would not operate in *g ∞reb ∞-.
Per Vasmer, Chernykh and Trubachev, this verb in fact derives from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞rob-√©ye-ti, from *g ∞reb-; see also Proto-Slavic *gret√¨. Chernykh describes it as the causative of *gret√¨.
Per Rix (LIV), probably from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞robh‚ÇÇ-√©ye-ti, from *g ∞rebh‚ÇÇ-, which allows for Winter's law and also accounts for the Sanskrit -(b)h- (but still doesn't account for the Germanic forms, which are supposed to derive from a different root *g ∞reb ∞-).

etm_info:
Product noun of *na- (‚Äúon‚Äù) +‚Äé *piti (‚Äúto drink‚Äù), from an earlier u-stem Proto-Slavic *napit—ä, extended with *-—äk—ä. Possibly traces back to Proto-Balto-Slavic *peitus[1], based on the comparison with Lithuanian pi·∫Ωt≈´s¬†pl (‚Äúlunch, dinner‚Äù). The Lithuanian lemma differs slightly in meaning (and moreover exhibits mobile AP 4), which makes the relation to the Slavic lemma questionable.
Comparison with other languages points towards possible descend from Proto-Indo-European *peHy- (‚Äúto feed, to drink‚Äù) (see *peh‚ÇÇ- (‚Äúto nourish‚Äù), *peh‚ÇÉ- (‚Äúto drink‚Äù)). This root has lost its laryngeal already in pre-Balto-Slavic times due to Pinault's rule, hence, there is no trace of acute in Balto-Slavic. Probably also cognate with Sanskrit ‡§™‡§ø‡§§‡•Å (pitu, ‚Äújuice, drink‚Äù) (see there for further discussion). It is possible that Proto-Indo-European *peyH- (‚Äúfat‚Äù) relates to the mentioned roots via Schwebeablaut.

Perhaps from *a- (‚Äúno-‚Äù) +‚Äé *≈°ƒçer—ä with second element possibly meaning:

‚Äúagile, nimble‚Äù in reference to the reptilian locomotion of lizards. Akin to Proto-Slavic *skor—ä (‚Äúspeedy, quick‚Äù), possibly *x—ärt—ä (‚Äúhound‚Äù), *ƒç—årt—ä (‚Äúdemon‚Äù). Further cognate with Lithuanian skƒór·ªπs, skƒór·∫Ωlis (‚Äúlocust‚Äù), Latvian ≈°ƒ∑√≠rga√Ælis (‚Äúlizard‚Äù).
‚Äúfur, pelt‚Äù in reference to the hairless skin of lizards. Akin to Proto-Slavic *skora (‚Äúhide‚Äù) and cognate with Albanian shqarr (‚Äúmarten‚Äù). Similar meaning is attested in secondary Russian —èÃÅ—â–µ—Ä (j√°≈°ƒçer, ‚Äúrough leather‚Äù). A variation of this hypothesis (due to Potebnja) proposes that the prefix *a- is instead a clipping of unattested *a—Ö—ä (‚Äúprickly, scrubby‚Äù), cognate with Sanskrit ‡§Ü‡§ñ‡•Å (ƒÅkh√∫, ‚Äúmole‚Äù), possibly Ancient Greek œÉŒ∫ŒØŒøœÖœÅŒøœÇ (sk√≠ouros, ‚Äúsquirrel‚Äù).
In either case, possibly cognate with Sanskrit ‡§Ü‡§∂‡•ç‡§ö‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø (ƒÅ≈õcarya, ‚Äúwonderful, marvelous‚Äù) (according to Machek).
Per Br√ºckner, may alternatively reflect *ask—ä (‚Äúburrow, hollow‚Äù) +‚Äé *-er—ä in view of some rare forms with alternative ending (in *-el—å, *-jur—ä). Effectively meaning ‚Äúburrow-dwelling animal‚Äù (even though lizards are not known to dig their lairs).

Over time, the term has undergone a semantic drift in certain thematic environments, giving rise to figurative terms such as Russian —Ç—Ä–æ–≥–∞—Ç—å (trogat π, ‚Äúto affect, to arouse emotionally‚Äù) and Bulgarian —Ç—Ä—ä–≥–≤–∞–º (tr«égvam), Macedonian —Ç—Ä–≥–Ω–µ (trgne, ‚Äúto depart‚Äù). etm_info:
Ultimately from Latin Caesar, the name of Julius Caesar, whose name became part of the Roman emperor's title. The name was very early borrowed into Germanic as *kaisaraz, whence it was borrowed into Slavic from an unknown source.
The most commonly regarded etymon cited in the literature is Gothic êå∫êå∞êåπêçÉêå∞êçÇ (kaisar), though such assignment is problematic. Old High German and Old Saxon forms with the suffix -ur are less plausible etymons. Formal mismatches with Gothic form include:

Germanic short */a/ regularly yields */o/ in Common Slavic, and the reconstructions for the vowel suffix point to a short */a/. The regular suffix from the Gothic form would have been **-or.
Even if we are dealing with analogical leveling to the productive agentive suffix *-ƒÅ≈ô—å, this still doesn't fully explain the short vowel. The Slovene form points to a short suffixal vowel, since the accent retracted from short final vowels.
If the short suffixal */-a-/ represents a late borrowing, after the Common Slavic rephonemicization of qualitative oppositions into quantitative ones, then this would exclude Gothic as the donor languages because the Goths lost their dominance in the Pontic region around the fifth century, well before such a process took place.
the C sound has been palatalized.

Trubachev, Derksen: From Proto-Indo-European *ge«µ ∞l√≥s (with oxytone accent on the last syllable), cognate with Old High German kegil (‚Äústake‚Äù).

Within this hypothesis, -z- in Slavic is problematic.
Mladenov, Georgiev: From an earlier Proto-Slavic *≈æegl—ä (‚Äúbranding needle, rod‚Äù), the l-participle of Proto-Slavic *≈æegti (‚Äúto heat up, to burn‚Äù), with assimilation of *-g- > *-z- (or -≈æ- in Serbo-Croatian) next to *≈æ-. Such an etymon still survives in Modern Bulgarian –∂–µ–≥—ä–ª (≈æeg«él).

etm_info:
1. Sometimes explained as a deverbative of *buƒçati (‚Äúto make noise, roar‚Äù) and reconstructed as *b—äƒçela. A bee is, therefore, the one that makes noise.
2. Alternatively from North-West Proto-Indo-European *b ∞i-k ∑e- (‚Äúbee, stinging insect‚Äù), an extension of root *b ∞i- (‚Äúto hit, strike‚Äù) - compare *biti (‚Äúto beat, hit‚Äù).
The Psalterium Sinaiticum contains the only Old Church Slavonic instance of –±—å—á–µ–ª–∞ (bƒ≠ƒçela) but since the form –±—ä—á–µ–ª–∞ (b≈≠ƒçela) is just as rare, it is impossible to precisely reconstruct the late Proto-Slavic form of this word on the basis of Old Church Slavonic. Since this Proto-Slavic word was an oxytone, none of the descendant languages retain a reflex of the medial weak jer.
Baltic cognates (Latvian bite, Lithuanian b√¨tƒó, Old Prussian bitte) would in that case render the Proto-Balto-Slavic forms as *bikelƒì and *bitƒì.
3. The root of the abovementioned Proto-Balto-Slavic forms may in turn be a cognate of the roots in Old Irish bech (Irish beach), Old High German bƒ´a, Old English bƒìo (English bee), Dutch bij, dialectal German Beie (German Biene), Old Norse b√Ω (Danish bi). If so, the ultimate source is Proto-Indo-European *b ∞ey-.

etm_info:
There are multiple theories:

Borrowed either from Old High German kenning (‚Äúsymbol, sign‚Äù) or from a different Germanic source (compare Gothic êå∫êåøêåΩêåΩêå∞êåΩ (kunnan, ‚Äúto know‚Äù) and Old Norse kunna (‚Äúto know‚Äù)).
From Akkadian kunukkum (‚Äúseal-cylinder‚Äù) or kanƒ´kum (‚Äúsealed object: document, sack bulla, etc.‚Äù), via Old Armenian ’Ø’∂’´÷Ñ (knik ø, ‚Äúseal‚Äù).
Ultimate Chinese origin, from Âç∑ (Middle Chinese k…£iu·¥ánX, k…£iu·¥ánH < Old Chinese *kror î (‚Äúto roll up‚Äù), *kror-s (‚Äúscroll‚Äù)), as paper was invented in China around the 1st century AD. However, this seems less likely due to the likely temporal precedence of Proto-Slavic over Early Middle Chinese and the large spatial separation of the donor and recipient languages.
The second and third theories require transmission by a Turkic or an Iranian language, but nothing is attested in them. Although sometimes cited, Chuvash –∫”ó–Ω–µ–∫–µ (kƒïnekÃ¨e) and Ossetian —á–∏–Ω—ã–≥ (·∏±inyg), –∫–∏—É–Ω—É–≥”ï (kiwnug√¶) are both considered early Slavic loans. However, Hungarian k√∂nyv (‚Äúbook‚Äù) and Erzya –∫–æ–Ω—ë–≤ (konjov, ‚Äúpaper‚Äù), which are unlikely to derive from Slavic, testify to the early presence of this word in the Volga region.

etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *au≈°(t)ra- (‚Äúdawn, morning‚Äù), from Proto-Indo-European *h‚ÇÇews-ro- (‚Äúof the dawn or morning, matutinal; eastern‚Äù), from *h‚ÇÇews- (‚Äúdawn; east‚Äù). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian au≈°r√†, dial. au≈°tr√† (‚Äúdawn‚Äù), Latvian √†ustra, a≈©stra (‚Äúdawn‚Äù). Indo-European cognates include Ancient Greek Œ±·ΩîœÅ·æ± (a√∫rƒÅ, ‚Äú(esp. cool) breeze, fresh air of the morning‚Äù), Latin auster (‚Äúsouth wind‚Äù), Proto-Germanic *austrƒÖ (‚Äúeast‚Äù), Proto-Germanic *Austr«≠ (‚ÄúEaster, springtime; name of a goddess‚Äù) (presumably from the goddess of the dawn, lust, fertility and spring, associated with the beginning of the year).
A variant *jutro appears in West Slavic, Slovenian and Serbo-Croatian, and is also attested in Old Church Slavonic, but considered secondary; there are further Slavic lexemes that display an alternation *ju- in West and South Slavic vs. *u- in East Slavic. Variants with *(j)ustr- point to *ustr- < *usr-,[1] the loss of -s- being either due to dissimilation[2] or perhaps due to the law of open syllables, if the -s- was variably assigned to the end of the first syllable. According to Kortlandt, the acute on the root implies a zero-grade variant (which would have parallels in Sanskrit ‡§â‡§∏‡•ç‡§∞ (usr√°-, ‚Äúreddish, ruddy, bright, matutinal‚Äù), ‡§â‡§∏‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ (usrƒÅÃÅ-, ‚Äúdawn, morning‚Äù)), which, however, is not attested.[3] The intrusive -t- is regular in Proto-Slavic, compare *ostr—ä, *strumy.

etm_info:
Etymology uncertain. Skok gives two hypotheses:

From a northern Turkic language, in the form ubyr or ubyrly (‚Äúwitch‚Äù). Compare Tatar —É–±—ã—Ä (ubƒ±r, ‚Äúvampiric witch‚Äù), Chuvash –≤—É–ø”ë—Ä (vupÃ¨ƒÉr, ‚Äúvampire‚Äù), Turkish obur (‚Äúglutton‚Äù), all from Proto-Turkic *≈çpur, possibly from Proto-Turkic *≈çp- (‚Äúto swallow, gulp down‚Äù).[1] Vasmer finds this phonetically doubtful.[2]
A Slavic construction, from *u- +‚Äé *py≈ô—å, ‚Äúflyer‚Äù with a privative prefix. Compare *netopy≈ô—å. According to this hypothesis *«´pyr—å could have originated as a taboo for *v—ålkolak—ä (cf. vukodlak).
Mel‚Äônyƒçuk offers a different explanation, a Slavic construction from *«´- +‚Äé *pyr-, ‚Äúnot burned‚Äù, with a privative prefix attached to a root meaning ‚Äúfire‚Äù. The word would then indicate an uncremated corpse. He also lists alternative suggestions that others had proposed: a possible connection with *py≈ô—å (‚Äúflyer‚Äù), as above; or from *v—ä- +‚Äé *pƒõr—å as a coinage related to vrƒõpiti (‚Äúto cling‚Äù), supposedly because a vampire bites and clings to its victims.
Mel‚Äônyƒçuk further proposes that the forms with initial vam- were derived by way of Old Church Slavonic *–≤—´–ø–∏—Ä—ä (*v«´pir≈≠) with prothetic *–≤-, borrowed into Byzantine Greek as Œ≤Œ±ŒºœÄœçœÅŒøœÇ (bamp√∫ros) and then borrowed back into the South Slavic languages.

etm_info:
Formed as **kol- +‚Äé *-ƒõno, of disputed origin. Proposed etymologies include:

From Proto-Indo-European *k ∑el- (‚Äúto turn, rotate‚Äù)[1] or *k ∑elh‚ÇÅ- (‚Äúto revolve‚Äù)[2]. Possibly, via s-extension, the origin of Latin collum (‚Äúneck‚Äù), Proto-Germanic *halsaz (‚Äúneck‚Äù).
From Proto-Indo-European *kelH- (‚Äúto rise, raise, lift‚Äù)[1], often claimed as the origin of Proto-Slavic *ƒçelo (‚Äúforehead‚Äù) and (first part of) *ƒçeƒæust—å (‚Äújaw‚Äù).
Occassionally compared to Ancient Greek œÉŒ∫Œ≠ŒªŒøœÇ (sk√©los, ‚Äúleg‚Äù), of disputed descent. Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kel- (‚Äúto bend, crook‚Äù).
Akin to Lithuanian k·∫Ωlis (‚Äúknee‚Äù), kelƒóÃÅnas (‚Äúknee joint‚Äù) and Latvian celis (‚Äúknee‚Äù). Arguably, further related to Ancient Greek Œ∫·ø∂ŒªŒøŒΩ (k√¥lon, ‚Äúmember, body part‚Äù), Ancient Greek Œ∫œÖŒªŒªœåœÇ (kull√≥s, ‚Äúcrooked, deformed‚Äù).
Secondary meaning ‚Äúlineage‚Äù is sometimes considered unrelated, commonly linked with *ƒçeƒæad—å (‚Äúoffsprings‚Äù) (collective) of uncertain origin. According to some interpretations, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)k ∑el- (‚Äúto rally (a group), to crowd‚Äù) (whence Proto-Germanic *skul≈ç (‚Äúcrowd, multitude‚Äù)).

By surface analysis, *s—ä- +‚Äé *dorv-. Exact origin is uncertain:

Per Meillet: from *s—äÃÄdorv—ä with accent shifted by Dybo's law, from Proto-Balto-Slavic *s√∫darwas, from Proto-Indo-European *h‚ÇÅsu-d ∞or-wo-, from *d ∞er- (‚Äúsupport, hold‚Äù). d ∞/dH is required to avoid Winter's law, which is reflected in Lithuanian ≈´.
Related to *d—år≈æati and Proto-Indo-Iranian *d ∞ruw√°s (‚Äúfirm, fixed‚Äù): Persian ÿØÿ±ŸàÿØ‚Äé, Avestan ê¨õê¨≠ê¨éê¨éê¨Ä‚Äé (druua, ‚Äúhealthy‚Äù) and possibly Proto-Finnic *terveh (‚Äúhealthy; whole‚Äù)[1].
From Proto-Indo-European *h‚ÇÅsu-dor(H)wo-, from *h‚ÇÅsu- (‚Äúwell, good‚Äù) + *d√≥ru (‚Äútree, wood‚Äù).
Related to *dervo (‚Äútree, wood‚Äù), *dr—ävo (‚Äútree, (pl.) wood‚Äù) and Lithuanian s≈´ÃÅdrus (‚Äúthick, dense‚Äù), Sanskrit ‡§∏‡•Å‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞‡•Å (sudr√∫)[2]. Further Albanian drenj√´/dreng (‚Äústrong, healthy‚Äù), Proto-Germanic *triwwiz (‚Äútrue‚Äù).
Compare Latin r≈çbustus (< r≈çbur), German kerngesund (< Kern).

Alternatively, borrowed from unattested Gothic *êå≤êå∞êåΩêçÉ (*gans) (due to its apparent "centum" character), from Proto-Germanic *gans, from Proto-Indo-European *«µ ∞h‚ÇÇ√©ns.

etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *kweistei. Related to Latvian kvit√™t (‚Äúto shimmer, to glimmer‚Äù).

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *·∏±weyt-, where Proto-Indo-European *·∏±w- is depalatalized to *kw- in Balto-Slavic before a back vowel but has its regular reflex ≈õw- before a front vowel, and the complex pattern of related Proto-Slavic words with *kv- and *sv- (see Related terms, below) is due to analogical changes in both directions.
Per Rix (LIV), there are two separate roots, Proto-Indo-European *·∏±weyt- (‚Äúto become bright‚Äù) and Proto-Indo-European *kweyt- (‚Äúto shine‚Äù), the latter found only in Balto-Slavic.
Chernykh refers to a substitution of "West-European" *k in place of *·∏±-, presumably suggesting a borrowing from a Centum language to the West of Proto-Balto-Slavic.
Trubachev's theory is of "secondary centumization", which appears to be essentially the same as Chernykh's.

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *paitei.

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *poyH-, from the root *peyH-. Cognate with Tocharian B pi- (‚Äúto sing, to make sing‚Äù).
Per Vasmer, connections outside of Slavic are unreliable. Possibly connected with Ancient Greek œÄŒ±ŒπŒ¨ŒΩ (pai√°n), œÄŒ±ŒπœéŒΩ (pai·πìn), Ionic œÄŒ±ŒπŒÆœâŒΩ (pai·∏ó≈çn, ‚Äúpaean, hymn in honor of Apollo‚Äù); sometimes also compared with Gothic êçÜêå∞êåπêå∞êåΩ (faian, ‚Äúto blame, to condemn‚Äù), Ancient Greek ·ºîŒºœÄŒ±ŒπŒøœÇ (√©mpaios, ‚Äúknowledgeable, intelligent‚Äù).
Per Trubachev, possibly originating as a causative of *piti (‚Äúto drink‚Äù), with the semantic change drink > sing going back to the pagan rite of sacrificial libation.
A derivation from Proto-Indo-European *pey- (‚Äúto adore‚Äù) is also possible despite lacking direct semantic basis. If so, cognates include  Latin pius (‚Äúpious, devout‚Äù) and  Old English f«£le (‚Äúfaithful, trusty, good; dear, beloved‚Äù)
The alternating Proto-Slavic stems *pƒõ- and *poj- are regular outcomes of the original Proto-Balto-Slavic *pai- before consonants and vowels respectively.

Doubtfully connected with Latin trah≈ç (‚Äúto drag‚Äù), Gothic êå∏êå∞êåπêçÇêå∫êçâ (√æairk≈ç, ‚Äúhole‚Äù).
Per Chernykh, from Proto-Indo-European *terg ∞-, extended version of *ter- (‚Äúto rub‚Äù), cognate with Proto-Slavic *terti, Latin ter≈ç.
Over time, the term has undergone a semantic drift in certain thematic environments, giving rise to figurative terms such as Russian —Ç—Ä–æ–≥–∞—Ç—å (trogat π, ‚Äúto affect, to arouse emotionally‚Äù) and Bulgarian —Ç—Ä—ä–≥–≤–∞–º (tr«égvam), Macedonian —Ç—Ä–≥–Ω–µ (trgne, ‚Äúto depart‚Äù). The later semantic development is analogous with Italian partire (‚Äúto go away‚Äù), French partir (‚Äúto depart‚Äù) which descend from Latin partƒ´re (‚Äúto separate‚Äù).

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞rob-√©ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞reb-; meanings "to rake" in daughter languages from confusion with the root *g ∞reb ∞- (see Proto-Slavic *gret√¨ (‚Äúto dig, to rake, to scrape‚Äù)). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian gr√≥bti (‚Äúto seize‚Äù), Latvian gr√¢bt (‚Äúto seize‚Äù). Indo-European cognates include Old Norse gr√°pa (‚Äúto seize‚Äù). The same confusion appears to have happened elsewhere; compare Sanskrit ‡§ó‡•É‡§π‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (g·πõh·πáƒÅÃÅti), ‡§ó‡•É‡§≠‡•ç‡§£‡§æ‡§§‡§ø (g·πõbh·πáƒÅÃÅti, ‚Äúto seize, to hold, to take‚Äù). Avestan: grab- ‚Äòto grab, seize, take‚Äô, Old Persian: grab- ‚Äòto seize (as possesion), Persian ⁄Øÿ±ŸÅÿ™ŸÜ‚Äé (gereftan), Ÿæÿ∞€åÿ±ŸÅÿ™ŸÜ‚Äé (paziroftan).[1] English grab vs. Gothic êå≤êçÇêå∞êå±êå∞êåΩ (graban, ‚Äúto dig‚Äù), all of which come from *g ∞reb ∞-. Derksen does not derive this verb from *g ∞reb ∞- due to Winter's law, which is required to produce the acute *-a- of the Slavic root but would not operate in *g ∞reb ∞-.
Per Vasmer, Chernykh and Trubachev, this verb in fact derives from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞rob-√©ye-ti, from *g ∞reb-; see also Proto-Slavic *gret√¨. Chernykh describes it as the causative of *gret√¨.
Per Rix (LIV), probably from Proto-Indo-European *g ∞robh‚ÇÇ-√©ye-ti, from *g ∞rebh‚ÇÇ-, which allows for Winter's law and also accounts for the Sanskrit -(b)h- (but still doesn't account for the Germanic forms, which are supposed to derive from a different root *g ∞reb ∞-).

etm_info:
Generally agreed to derive from Old High German Karl, name of the Frankish ruler Charlemagne (742-814) who ruled the western areas of Slavdom, from Proto-Germanic *karilaz (‚Äúfree man‚Äù).
Extended derivation:

Old High German Karl > Late Proto-Slavic *k√µrƒæ—å
The shift from hard o-stem to the soft jo-stem, as outlined in the chronology above, has several theories of origin:

Holzer explains the j-suffix as originating from a substantivized possessive adjective
Schenker suggests analogical replacement after agent nouns ending in *-teƒæ—å or other words denoting leaders such as *cƒõsa≈ô—å and *k—änƒôdz—å
Pronk-Tiethoff suggests the final *-ƒæ—å is due to the fact that Proto-Slavs likely perceived the Old High German final consonant as soft, similarly as in the loanword *grƒôdeƒæ—å.
The word has been described as "without doubt the most famous Germanic loanword in Slavic" (Pronk-Tiethoff 2013) due to the fact that it's the only loanword in Slavic that can actually be dated, thus giving clues to the absolute dating of Proto-Slavic phonological developments. The fact that it regularly underwent historical Proto-Slavic sound laws, and that it's reflected in all three branches, is one of the chief indications to date Late Proto-Slavic (Common Slavic) to the ninth century.
However, this is comparatively late (only a century before Old Church Slavonic manuscripts were written), so other etymologies have been suggested:

Holzer derives it from the name of the Frankish ruler Charles Martel (688-741). The issue with this theory is that Charles Martel was not particularly important to the contemporary Slavs.
Stender-Petersen derives it from Proto-Germanic *kar(i)laz (‚Äúfree man‚Äù) (Old High German karl (‚Äúman‚Äù)) with a semantic shift explained as "very ordinary".
These theories are generally thought of as less convincing than from Karl "Charlemagne", who was an actual king of (some) Slavs.

etm_info:
Of Germanic origin, with two proposed sources of borrowing:

For meaning beech: From Proto-West Germanic *b≈çku (‚Äúbeech‚Äù)[1][2], formally equivalent to *buk—ä (‚Äúbeech‚Äù) +‚Äé *-y.
For meaning books, writs: From Gothic êå±êçâêå∫êçâêçÉ¬†pl (b≈çk≈çs, ‚Äúbooks‚Äù) (per Vasmer, Trubachev).
The intrinsic relation between the two meanings is sometimes disputed (e.g. by Kluge), since there is no survived evidence for beech-based writing among early Germanic and Balto-Slavic people. It is possible (as noted by Mallory and Adams) that beech had religious significance for ancient Indo-European people and so was used to inscribe sacred symbols onto[2]. In this case, the extended meaning writ, sign would be directly borrowed from Germanic. A third hypothesis speculates that beechmast was used for counting and bookkeeping, whence the word innately developed a sense of ‚Äúunit of data representation‚Äù ‚Üí grapheme, writ.

S≈Çawski derives the set of meanings "protection, guard, defense; object of protecting, defending, gate, dam, barrier, fortification" as an action noun of the verb *borniti (‚Äúto guard, protect, defend‚Äù). Derksen legitimizes separate treatment due to the semantic difficulties of connecting Common Slavic *borti (‚Äúto fight, conquer‚Äù) as well as other Indo-European cognates (Latin feri≈ç (‚Äúto hit, strike‚Äù), Old Norse berja (‚Äúto beat, hit‚Äù)) with the root *b ∞erh‚ÇÉ- (‚Äúto hit with a sharp instrument‚Äù).
